attri_ht:
['Page 6:
[¬s]"Over the duration of the study, the sample decreased from 276 to
241 (a 14.5% decrease). The percentage of attrition was greater for
the control group (19% attrition for the control group; 5% attrition
for the intervention group). To test for differential attrition between
the groups, t-tests were conducted based on demographic char-
acteristics (child age, gender, ELL status, parent education, marital
status, maternal age) and baseline self-regulation and achievement
scores. No signiﬁcant differences emerged between the groups sug-
gesting that although attrition was higher in the control group,
there were no signiﬁcant differences between the groups in demo-
graphic characteristics at baseline."
"Seven children switched classrooms during the study period,
however, six of these children changed classrooms after the inter-
vention had taken place and one of the children moved from one
control classroom to another during the intervention[¬e]"', 'Page 8:

tion such that children were analyzed as if they remained in the
group to which they were originally assigned (Fisher et al., 1990).
This is thought to be a conservative and practical approach for"
"handling attrition[¬e]"']
